":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":11,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":21,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":31,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Coigniers II was born in 1075, in Durham, England, his father, Roger I DeCogneries, was 35 and his mother, Matilda, was 32. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Roger Coigniers. He died in 1128, in Durham, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1075–1128":"1075–1128","1078–Female":"1078–Surnud","1105–Male":"1105–Surnud","1040–1101":"1040–1101","1044–Female":"1044–Surnud","1128":"1128","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1101":"1101","1078":"1078","1044":"1044","1075":"1075","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Abt 1072":"umbes 1072","1040":"1040","Sockburne, Durham":"Durham, England","Durham, England":"Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Durham, Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","<Of Howton,Coigniers,France>":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi